  <text name="tacticalHelp" >
    <page>
      <p>Xenowar - How to Play</p>
      <p>
        The game is turn based like a traditional board game. You take a
        turn, the aliens takes a turn, until one team is blasted
        into oblivion.
      </p>
      <p>
        The following screens cover the basics; much more info on-line
        at xenowar.net
      </p>
      <p>You can also access the game Settings from this help screen.</p>
    </page>
    <page image="helpImage7">
      <p>[Moving the Camera]</p>
      <p system="pc">
        Left click and drag to scroll around the map.
      </p>
      <p system="pc">
        Right click and drag to zoom and rotate.
      </p>
      <p system="android">
        You can drag the map with your finger, or pinch with 2
        fingers to zoom. The trackball/wheel also zooms and rotates.
      </p>
      <p>
        If you tap the orbit button (pictured) your next drag
        will rotate and zoom the camera. It is a quick way
        to adjust the view.
      </p>
      
    </page>
    <page image="helpImage2">
      <p>[Select a Unit]</p>
      <p>
        You can select a unit by tapping on the tile where it stands.
      </p>
      <p system="pc">
        The keyboard left/right arrow keys will also select units. control-left/right rotate.
        Pressing your 'u' key will hide the superfluous on-screen UI.
      </p>
    </page>

    <page image="helpImage2">
      <p>[Move a Unit]</p>
      <p>
        You can tap the destination for unit (any colored ground
        location) and it will move there.
      </p>
      <p>
        You can also drag a unit to move it.
      </p>
      <p>
        If Confirm Movement is turned ON in the Settings, you need to accept or cancel the path shown.
        You can select a new destination before accepting.
      </p>
    </page>

    <page>
      <p>[Moving on your turn]</p>
      <p>
        When it is your turn, you may move
        as many units as you like. But each
        unit has a certain amount of Time
        Units (TU) per turn. One time unit
        allows one space of movement. The
        circles on the ground show the
        range of movement for the unit.
      </p>
    </page>

    <page>
      <p>[Time Units (TU)]</p>
      <p>
        Shooting also consumes TU. The color of the circle indicates how
        much time is remaining after you move to that location. 
        Green for an aimed shot, Yellow for a fast shot,
        and Orange indicates no time left to shoot.
      </p>
      <p>
        Inventory management and rotation consume no Time Units.
      </p>
    </page>

    <page image="helpImage0">
      <p>[UI Menu]</p>
      <p>
        From top to bottom, the icons are: 1) Abort mission. The lander takes off
        with whoever is, or isn't, on board. 2) Help 3) End turn.
        You are done moving and the aliens move. 4) Target a location on the map.
        Tap any location on the map to shoot there. 5) Inventory and character screen.
      </p>
    </page>


    <page image="helpImage1">
      <p>[Unit Menu]</p>
      <p>
        Rotate left and rotate right rotates the currently selected unit. Left and right
        selects different units.
      </p>
      <p system="pc">
        Remember you can also use the keyboard, and press the 'u' key to hide the control UI.
      </p>
    </page>

    <page image="helpImage3" >
      <p>[Shooting UI]</p>
      <p>
        Left click on your
        target to display shot choices,
        including info about the type of
        shot, the approximate odds of hitting,
        and ammo remaining. Every
        weapon is different!
      </p>
      <p>
        The color block on the right is
        the amount of TU left after you fire.
      </p>
    </page>

    <page>
      <p>[Reaction fire]</p>
      <p>
        Reaction fire occurs when your units fire at the aliens during
        the alien turn. It is key to an effective defense.
      </p>
      <p>
        For reaction fire to occur, you must have enough TU left over
        by ending your move in the Green or Yellow circles.
      </p>
      <p>
      Rotation greatly impacts reaction fire. Make sure you end your
      turn facing where you think the aliens are hiding!
      </p>
    </page>

  </text>

  <text name="characterHelp" >
    <page>
      <p>[Unit Screen]</p>
      <p>Use this screen to pick up and drop items, wear armor, and select a weapon. You can also view statistics
         about the current unit.</p>
      <p>The name of the weapon the unit is holding is displayed in the top left. Beside the name is the tech level, from 1 to 3.
         Higher tech levels indicate better weapons and armor.</p>
    </page>
    <page image="helpImage4">
      <p>[Inventory]</p>
      <p>
        What the unit is carrying. The top row is in use: the currently worn armor and currently carried
        weapon. You can tap to drop an item, or drag to organize items.</p>
      <p>
        For weapons, the total rounds available for that weapon is displayed below the name.
      </p>
    </page>

    <page image="helpImage5">
      <p>[Items on the Ground]</p>
      <p>
       The row of tabs select Terran Weapons, Alien Weapons, Armor/Shields,
       and Miscellaneous items. Tap to select a group to view. Tap an item to pick it up.
      </p>
      <p>
        The number of items available is displayed beneath the item name.
      </p>
    </page>

    <page>
      <p>[Stats and Numbers]</p>
      <p> The lower right buttons show unit traits, abilities, and statistics.</p>
      <p> 'Inv' is the default inventory screen. 'Stats' shows the unit statistics. 'Wpns' compares 
      weapons carried and on the ground at 8m range.</p>
    </page>
  </text>

  <text name="introHelp" >
    <page>
      <p>[Xenowar]</p>
      <p>Xenowar. Copyright 2011 Lee Thomason / Grinning Lizard Software.</p>
      <p>
        Welcome to Xenowar! Xenowar is an alien blasting strategy game. You can
        submit feedback, read the community forum, or get more gameplay information
        at xenowar.net.
      </p>
      <p> The buttons on the lower right navigate help, the lower left exits help.</p>
    </page>
    <page>
      <p>[Overview]</p>
      <p>
        Xenowar combines strategic and tactical games.</p>
		<p>The strategic game is the geo-scape where you build bases, defend against
        UFOs, research, and allocate resources in real time. When ground combat occurs,
        the tactical game is turn based combat.
      </p>
    </page>
    <page>
      <p>[Getting Started]</p>
      <p>'Continue' resumes the game in progress.</p>
      <p>'New Game' brings up the new game choices. Starting a new game will delete
	      any game in progress. After selecting 'New Game', tap 'New Geo' to play the full game, 
		  or 'New Tactical' to play a 
          single battle.</p>
      <p>The game auto-saves at exit.</p>
      <!--<p>If you choose a new game, you can select the skill level and number of your squad, the skill level and 
         number of aliens, and the terrain for the battle.
       </p>-->
      <p>Good luck and have fun!</p>
    </page>
  </text>

  <text name="geoHelp" >
    <page>
      <p>[Xenowar]</p>
      <p>The geo view shows the world, its nations, and the state of the alien invasion.</p>
      <p>
        The strategic part of the game is played out on this screen, in real time.
        When combat occurs, it is turn based on the tactical screen.
      </p>
      <p>You can also access the game Settings from this help screen.</p>
    </page>
    <page>
      <p>[Main UI]</p>
      <p>
        The upper left button takes you to the research screen.
      </p>
      <p>
        The lower left toggles base building. With this button down, tap on the
        map to build a base. Start the game by building a base. Your first base
        comes fully provisioned.
      </p>
      <p>
        The lower right display shows your current cash in megadollars.
      </p>
      <p>Tap and drag to scroll the display. You can tap a base or grounded
         UFO for additional menus.</p>
    </page>
    <page image="helpImage6">
      <p>[Regions]</p>
      <p>There are 6 geo-political regions: North, South, Europe, Asia, Africa, and Under.
         Beneath the name of each region is a bar that indicates the amount of alien 
         influence.</p>
      <p>Each region has its own traits. Regions can be 1) capitalistic (better 
         sell prices), 2) militaristic (better soldiers), 3) scientific (faster research),
         4) high tech (make tech-3 weapons), or 5) manufacturing (make tech-3 armor).</p>
    </page>
    <page>
      <p>[Alien Invasion]</p>
      <p>Aliens initially generate influence with crop circles. With more influence, the aliens will
         mount city attacks or even attack your bases.</p>
      <p>
        When attacking, be aware that night fights are more
        difficult than day fights, and a normal UFO is harder to assault than a crashed one.
      </p>
      <p>You win the game by destroying the alien base. You'll lose the game if the aliens
         occupy all the world capitals.</p>      
    </page>
    <page>
      <p>[Base Options]</p>
      <p>Tapping any base brings up the base options.</p>
      <p>Supply: Purchases and sells supplies from the host region. A base must have a 
         'cargo' facility to use supply.</p>
      <p>Equip: Equip the base squad, see unit stats, and compare weapons. A base must 
         have a 'cargo' and 'troops' facility to have units.</p>
      <p>Build: Build base facilities.</p>
    </page>
    <page>
      <p>[UFO Options]</p>
      <p>Tapping a crashed or invading UFO brings up a list of 
         bases that can send troops. Tap the base name to send a lander.</p>
      <p>The lander carries troops to and from the battle. It can even retrieved
         unconscious units and make an escape from the field.</p>
      <p>
        If the battle is successful, items gathered from the battle field will
        be placed in the base's storage. Items needed for research
        are automatically applied.
      </p>
    </page>
    
  </text>

  <text name="buildBaseHelp" >
    <page>
      <p>[Build Base Help]</p>
      <p>Here you can buy base facilities. Tap on the facility, it will be built, 
         and funds deducted from you treasury.</p>
      <p>Troops: purchases and lander and barracks so troops can be hired for missions. 
         Missile: long range weapons.
         Cargo: a cargo lander allows selling and purchasing from the host region. 
         Guns: short range weapons.
         SciLab: allows the recruitment of scientists for research. </p>
    </page>
  </text>

  <text name="supplyBaseHelp" >
    <page>
      <p>[Supply Base Help]</p>
      <p>Tap to move items from the base storage (on the left) to the region's supply ship (on the right). 
      The "Sell All" toggle, when on, will sell all items in a slot with a single tap.</p>
      <p>Ammo clips refill after battle. (Which is reflected in their cost.) Tech-3 items
         can only be purchased from regions with the required traits.</p>
      <p>You can hire soldiers and scientists by purchasing them in the region's Alien tab.</p>
    </page>
  </text>

  <text name="researchHelp" >
    <page>
      <p>[Research]</p>
      <p>This scene shows the current research project, and options for other research you can do.
         Research is applied over time, and is directly proportional to the number of scientists 
         in your bases.</p>
      <p>Beneath the name of each research task is items required to begin that task.</p>
    </page>
    
  </text>

